{
  "terms": [
    {
      "term": "Ring Final Circuit",
      "simpleDefinition": "A power circuit that forms a continuous loop, starting and ending at the same protective device in the consumer unit.",
      "anchor": "A loop that starts and ends at the same point.",
      "misconception": "Thinking any circuit with multiple sockets is automatically a ring."
    },
    {
      "term": "Radial Circuit",
      "simpleDefinition": "A circuit that runs from the consumer unit to the final point of use without returning to the start.",
      "anchor": "A single path from start to finish.",
      "misconception": "Believing radial circuits are only used for lighting and not for power."
    },
    {
      "term": "SWA (Steel Wire Armoured)",
      "simpleDefinition": "A cable with a layer of steel wires for high mechanical protection, typically used for underground or industrial installations.",
      "anchor": "The 'armour' protects against physical impact.",
      "misconception": "Thinking SWA is suitable for internal domestic wiring where flexibility is needed."
    },
    {
      "term": "MICC (Mineral Insulated Copper Clad)",
      "simpleDefinition": "A fire-resistant cable made of copper conductors inside a copper sheath with mineral insulation, used in high-risk fire areas.",
      "anchor": "The ultimate fire-proof cable.",
      "misconception": "Confusing MICC with standard fire-resistant thermoplastic cables."
    },
    {
      "term": "Conduit",
      "simpleDefinition": "A tube-like enclosure (PVC or metal) used to protect cables and allow them to be drawn in or replaced easily.",
      "anchor": "A protective tube for single-core cables.",
      "misconception": "Thinking conduit is only for looks rather than mechanical protection."
    },
    {
      "term": "Trunking",
      "simpleDefinition": "A rectangular enclosure with a removable lid used to house and protect multiple circuits.",
      "anchor": "A box-section path for many cables.",
      "misconception": "Confusing trunking with conduit, which is circular and lacks a removable lid."
    },
    {
      "term": "Wiring System",
      "simpleDefinition": "The combination of the specific cable type and the containment method used to install it.",
      "anchor": "The physical 'how' and 'what' of the installation.",
      "misconception": "Thinking 'wiring system' refers only to the circuit diagram or electrical path."
    },
    {
      "term": "Hazardous Environment",
      "simpleDefinition": "An area where there is a risk of explosion or fire due to the presence of flammable gases, vapors, or dust.",
      "anchor": "High-risk zones requiring specialized protection.",
      "misconception": "Assuming 'hazardous' only refers to outdoor or wet locations."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "A ring final circuit is a loop that returns to its origin.",
    "Radial circuits follow a single path to the end of the line.",
    "SWA provides mechanical protection in tough environments.",
    "Containment like trunking and conduit protects cables from the environment.",
    "The wiring system must match the specific environment it is installed in."
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "Confusing a circuit's electrical path with its physical containment.",
    "Assuming all power circuits must be rings.",
    "Using domestic-grade cables in industrial or agricultural settings.",
    "Believing that data and control circuits operate on the same principles as high-power heating circuits."
  ]
}

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "key": "203-3a-teach-check-1",
      "title": "Circuit Types and Principles",
      "objective": "Describe the principles of operation for standard circuit types.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "In electrical installations, we categorize circuits by how they deliver power from the source to the load. A radial circuit is the most straightforward: it runs in a single path from the consumer unit to the final point of use. You will commonly see radials used for lighting, smoke alarms, and high-power dedicated appliances like electric showers or cookers.",
        "In contrast, a ring final circuit is a continuous loop. It starts at the protective device in the consumer unit, visits every socket outlet in the circuit, and then returns to that same protective device. This loop allows current to flow in two directions simultaneously, which effectively shares the load across the conductors and allows for a higher current rating than a single radial of the same cable size.",
        "Beyond standard power, we also install specialized circuits for data communications and control. These operate on different principles than high-power heating circuits, often carrying low-voltage signals rather than heavy current. It is vital to distinguish between these; a ring is specifically a power loop, whereas a radial is a 'dead-end' run. Selecting the correct circuit type ensures the system meets the functional needs of the building without overloading cables."
      ],
      "hint": "Think about whether the cable forms a complete loop back to the fuse board or ends at the last socket."
    },
    {
      "key": "203-3a-teach-check-2",
      "title": "Wiring Systems and Environments",
      "objective": "Identify suitable wiring systems for specific installation environments.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "A wiring system is the combination of the specific cable type and the containment method used to protect it. The environment of the installation is the primary factor in choosing these components. In a standard domestic setting, thermoplastic flat profile cable (often called twin and earth) is the standard because it is cost-effective and easy to install within walls.",
        "However, in industrial or commercial environments, cables face a higher risk of mechanical impact. In these areas, we use containment like conduit—protective PVC or metal tubes for single-core cables—or trunking, which are rectangular enclosures with removable lids for housing multiple circuits. For heavy-duty protection or underground runs, Steel Wire Armoured (SWA) cable is used because its outer 'armour' layer resists physical damage.",
        "Hazardous environments or high-risk fire areas require even more specialized systems. Mineral Insulated Copper Clad (MICC) cable is used for its extreme fire resistance. In agricultural settings, the wiring system must withstand moisture and corrosive chemicals. Always match the containment, such as tray or ladder racking, and the cable type to the specific environmental stresses to prevent premature failure."
      ],
      "hint": "Consider the difference between a house, a factory, and a farm; each needs a different level of physical protection for the cables."
    }
  ]
}

